    Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);
    HashMap<String, Integer> citiesToVertexMapping = new HashMap<>();
    System.out.println("Enter number of cities in the graph:");
    int noOfVertices = s.nextInt();
    System.out.println("Enter all the cities:");
    for(int i = 0; i < noOfVertices; i++){
        String city = s.nextLine();
        citiesToVertexMapping.put(city, i);
    }

    int noOfVertices = s.nextInt();
    nextInt() reads only the integer, but does NOT consume the newline (\n) left after pressing Enter.

    So the next call:
    String city = s.nextLine();
    immediately reads that leftover newline — which is an empty string "".
    Therefore, your first insertion becomes: citiesToVertexMapping.put("", 0);

    Fix: Consume the leftover newline once after nextInt():
        int noOfVertices = s.nextInt();
        s.nextLine(); // <-- consume the leftover newline

Key Learning No8:
    Q1. You used a hashmap as a cache key and entries disappeared, why?
    A mutable object is used as the key in a HashMap and that object is modified after insertion.
    Example (classic interview + real prod bug)
    class User {
        String userId;
        String role;

        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            return Objects.hash(userId, role);
        }

        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object o) {
            if (this == o) return true;
            if (!(o instanceof User)) return false;
            User u = (User) o;
            return Objects.equals(userId, u.userId)
                && Objects.equals(role, u.role);
        }
    }

    Map<User, String> cache = new HashMap<>();
    User user = new User();
    user.userId = "123";
    user.role = "USER";
    cache.put(user, "cachedData");

    // later…
    user.role = "ADMIN";
    cache.get(user); // returns null 😵

    How to fix it :
    Keys must be immutable. Use String, UUID, Long, etc or make key class: final / fields final -- equals/hashCode based only on immutable fields

    Q2. HashMap with multi-threading:
    Requirement: Multiple threads read & write to a cache. Same key might be accessed at the same time. No data corruption. No duplicate DB calls

    Case 1: HashMap (what goes wrong)
    Map<String, String> cache = new HashMap<>();

    String getData(String key) {
        if (!cache.containsKey(key)) {
            String value = loadFromDB(key);   // expensive
            cache.put(key, value);
        }
        return cache.get(key);
    }
    Two threads: T1 and T2
    Both call getData("A") at the same time.

    T1: containsKey("A") -> false
    T2: containsKey("A") -> false
    T1: loadFromDB("A")
    T2: loadFromDB("A")   ❌ duplicate DB hit
    T1: put("A", value1)
    T2: put("A", value2)

    Case 2: synchronizedMap (works but slow)
    Map<String, String> cache =
        Collections.synchronizedMap(new HashMap<>());
    Now:
    Thread safety ✔
    But every operation locks the entire map

    What happens
    T1: get("A")  (lock entire map)
    T2: get("B")  (blocked ❌)
    T3: put("C")  (blocked ❌)
    Even unrelated keys block each other.

    Case 3: ConcurrentHashMap (correct + scalable)
    ConcurrentHashMap<String, String> cache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    String getData(String key) {
        return cache.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> loadFromDB(k));
    }
    What happens internally
    Step-by-step with two threads
    T1: computeIfAbsent("A")
        → bucket for "A" is empty
        → lock ONLY bucket("A")
        → loadFromDB("A")
        → put value

    T2: computeIfAbsent("A")
        → sees value already present
        → returns it
    ✔ DB called once
    ✔ No corruption
    ✔ No global lock

    Why this works (key differences):

    Bucket-level locking
    Only the bucket for "A" is locked. Other keys still accessible
    T1 → bucket("A")  locked
    T2 → bucket("B")  free
    T3 → bucket("C")  free


