Key Learning No10:
    While working on a legacy Java project recently, I noticed something very common in older codebases:

    👉 String concatenation inside log statements

    Most of us have written logs like this at some point:
    logger.info("Order Id: " + orderId + " processed for user " + userId);
    Looks simple. Works fine.

    But behind the scenes, something unnecessary is happening 👇
    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    ⚠️ The Hidden Problem

    When we use string concatenation in logging:
    • Java creates new String objects in memory
    • This happens even if the log level is disabled
    • It causes unnecessary CPU and memory usage

    In high-traffic systems, this impact grows quickly.

    It becomes even more noticeable in cron-based or batch services, where logs run repeatedly inside loops and scheduled jobs, silently creating thousands of unnecessary objects.
    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    ✅ The Better Approach: Parameterized Logging

    logger.info("Order Id: {} processed for user {}", orderId, userId);
    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    💡 Why this is better
    ✔ No unnecessary object creation
    ✔ Formatting happens only when log level is enabled
    ✔ Cleaner and more readable code
    ✔ Recommended best practice in SLF4J & Log4j
    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    🧠 Real-World Insight

    Many legacy projects still use concatenation logging because it was never revisited.
    Refactoring these logs may look like a small change, but in large systems and scheduled jobs, it can bring clear performance gains over time.
    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    🎯 Takeaway

    Performance tuning is not always about big architectural changes.
    Sometimes it's about fixing small, silent inefficiencies hiding in plain sight.

    ✨ Parameterized logging is one of those tiny upgrades that makes your code smarter.


Key Learning No11:
    The code looked fine:

    @Value("${api.key}")
    private String apiKey;

    public MyService() {
      System.out.println(apiKey); // null
    }

    The problem: I was accessing the value inside the constructor.
    Spring injects @Value AFTER the object is created. Inside the constructor, it is always null.

    The fix:

    @Value("${api.key}")
    private String apiKey;

    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
      System.out.println(apiKey); // works
    }

    Use @PostConstruct if you need injected values during initialization.
    Constructor runs first. Injection happens after.

Key Learning No12:
    Why saveAll() is slow for 500k records ?
    1. Memory Overhead: Hibernate/JPA keeps all these entities in the "Persistence Context" (the first-level cache). Managing 500,000 objects in memory creates massive garbage collection overhead and consumes significant RAM.
    2. Transaction Management: You are likely running this within a single long-running transaction. If the database or the application crashes at minute 14, the entire 15 minutes of work is rolled back.
    3. Lack of Batching: Unless explicitly configured, many JPA implementations will still send these records to the database one by one, or in sub-optimal chunks, leading to hundreds of thousands of round-trips to the DB.

    Recommended Solutions
    1. Implement Manual Batching
    Instead of passing the whole list to saveAll(), break the list into smaller chunks (e.g., 500 or 1,000 records) and clear the persistence context periodically.

    int batchSize = 1000;
    for (int i = 0; i < trialBalanceEntities.size(); i++) {
        trialBalanceDAOService.save(trialBalanceEntities.get(i));
        if (i % batchSize == 0 && i > 0) {
            // Ensure your DAO/Service flushes and clears the EntityManager here
            trialBalanceDAOService.flushAndClear();
        }
    }

    When you do:

    saveAll(batch);
    entityManager.flush();

    Step-by-step:
        saveAll() -- Entities become managed, stored in Hibernate’s Persistence Context (1st-level cache)
        flush() -- Hibernate generates SQL, Executes INSERTs in DB
        After flush()
        ✅ DB is updated
        ❌ Entities are STILL in memory
        ❌ Still tracked for dirty checking

    ❗ Why Hibernate does this (by design)
    Hibernate assumes:
        You might still modify entities
        You may need:
        Lazy loading
        Dirty checking
        Cascading updates
        So it keeps everything managed

    ✅ What clear() does
        entityManager.clear();
            Detaches ALL entities
            Empties persistence context
        After this:

        Persistence Context: EMPTY ✅

    ⚖️ Flush vs Clear (important distinction)
    Operation	DB Write	Memory Cleanup
    flush()	✅ Yes	❌ No
    clear()	❌ No	✅ Yes
    🧾 Final line for your notes
    👉 flush() writes data to DB, but entities remain managed in persistence context.
    Only clear() frees memory by detaching them.

    This is exactly why your final solution works:

    saveAll(batch);
    flush();   // push to DB
    clear();   // free memory

Key Learning No13:
    JPA ID Generation Strategies – Summary:
    🔴 1. IDENTITY
        @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
        DB auto-generates ID (auto-increment)
        ❌ No JDBC batching
        ❌ One DB call per insert → slow
        👉 Use only for low-volume inserts

    🟢 2. SEQUENCE ⭐ (Best choice)
        @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE)
        Uses DB sequence
        IDs fetched in bulk
        ✅ Supports batching
        ✅ High performance
        ✅ Scales well

        👉 Best for bulk inserts / batch jobs

    Final Takeaway
    👉 SEQUENCE is the only strategy suitable for high-volume inserts

